title: Epstein Files Released As Pressure Mounts For Full Disclosure | 10 News
description: The US Justice Department has released hundreds of thousands of pages from its investigations into Jeffrey Epstein and Ghislaine Maxwell, following a new transparency law passed by Congress.  The first batch of documents was made public on Friday, with officials saying more records are still under review and will be released in the coming weeks.  Many of the files were heavily redacted to protect victims and ongoing investigations, and it remains unclear how much new information they contain.  The documents include multiple references and photos of former US president Bill Clinton, while making scant mention of President Donald Trump.  Lawmakers have criticised delays in the rollout, saying the law requires all unclassified Epstein-related material to be made public. title: Woman Charged After Alleged Carjacking And Dramatic Sydney Police Takedown | 10 News
description: A woman is tonight behind bars accused of a terrifying carjacking that saw another woman try to flee from a moving van and the vehicle chased through western Sydney streets before it was rammed by officers in a dramatic takedown.   The accused is now facing a string of charges with police alleging the delivery van was one of two vehicles she'd stolen. title: Biosecurity Dogs On Alert As Christmas Deliveries Spike | 10 News
description: More than 100 million parcels are expected to be delivered to homes across the country in the lead up to Christmas, but beyond the posties, there's also a crack team of canines protecting our borders. title: Nicki Minaj Praises Trump, Calls JD Vance An ‘Assassin’ To Charlie Kirk’s Widow | 10 News
description: Rapper Nicki Minaj has made a surprise appearance at a Turning Point USA convention in Arizona, using her time on stage to praise President Donald Trump and Vice President JD Vance.  Minaj was interviewed by Erika Kirk, the widow of Charlie Kirk, about her newly found support for Trump despite condemning him in the past.  There was an unfortunate awkward moment when the star praised “the assassin JD Vance,” leading to a few seconds of silence and laughter from the audience, with Kirk’s husband Charlie having been fatally shot in September.  "Dear young men, you have amazing role models like our handsome, dashing president, and you have amazing role models like the assassin, JD Vance, our vice president," Minaj said before looking down and covering her mouth. title: Netanyahu Honours Bondi Victims In Jerusalem Chabad Hanukkah Ceremony | 10 News
description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has commemorated victims of the Bondi Beach Shooting with Chabad emissaries on Sunday to light the last candle of Hanukkah in Jerusalem.  Netanyahu said the attack during a Hanukkah celebration in Sydney last week, where 15 people were killed and dozens wounded, will not break the spirit of the Jewish people.  “But I say from the depth of our hearts we share in the grief, but we also see the greatness, and we are more determined than ever to ensure the eternity of Israel,” Netanyahu said. title: LIVE: NSW Premier Chris Minns To Address New Laws Following Bondi Beach Shooting | 10 News
description: NSW Premier Chris Minns is addressing the media after he recalled parliament to introduce new laws that would tighten gun control, deal with hate speech and give police new powers when dealing with protestors.

title: Nine Killed & 10 Injured After Mass Shooting At South African Pub | 10 News
description: Nine people have died and at least 10 others wounded after a group of gunmen carried out a shooting at a South African pub during the early hours of Sunday.  Police say around 12 unknown suspects in a white mini-bus and a silver sedan opened fire at patrons at KwaNoxolo tavern in Johannesburg's Bekkersdal township just before 1am and continued to shoot randomly as they fled the scene.  It is the second mass shooting to happen in South Africa in three weeks, after gunmen killed a dozen people, including a three-year-old child, at a tavern near Pretoria on December 6.
